<subsection xml:id="subsec-combined-operations-involving-addition-and-subtraction">
    <title>Combined operations involving addition and subtraction.</title>
    <p>
       To perform combined operations involving addition and subtraction of fractions, follow the steps below: 
    </p>
    <p>
    <m>\textbf{Step 1}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
     Convert mixed numbers to improper fractions i.e for <m> 5 \frac{1}{3}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow> 5 \frac{1}{3} =\amp \frac{3 \times 5 + 1}{3} </mrow>
            <mrow> =\amp \frac{16}{3} </mrow>
        </md>  
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>\textbf{Step 2}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Find the LCM of the denominators if the fractions have different denominators.
      The LCM is the smallest number that both denominators can divide into.
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>\textbf{Step 3}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Rewrite the fractions so that it has the same denominator i.e.
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>\frac{2}{3} + \frac{1}{4}</m>  <m>= \frac{8+3}{12}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
     <m>\textbf{Step 4}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
       Once the fractions have the same denominator, you can perform the addition or subtraction of the fractions e.g., for addition case:
    </p>
    <p>
       <md>
        <mrow>\frac{2}{3} + \frac{1}{4} =\amp \frac{8+3}{12} </mrow>
        <mrow> =\amp \frac{11}{12}</mrow>
       </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        For subtraction case ,then:
    </p>
    <p>
       <md>
        <mrow>\frac{2}{3} - \frac{1}{4} =\amp \frac{8-3}{12} </mrow>
        <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{12} </mrow>
       </md>
       
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>\textbf{Step 5}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Simplify the result if the numerator and denominator have any common factors, by dividing both by their GCD.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                
            </p>
            <p>
               Cheruto is helping a chef prepare a recipe for a grade <m>8</m> end year celebration cake. The ingredients of the recipe are:
            </p>
            <p>
                Flour: <m>\frac{3}{4}</m> of a cup
            </p>
            <p>
                Sugar: <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> of a cup
            </p>
            <p>
                Butter: <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> of a cup   
            </p>
            <p>
                Milk: <m>\frac{5}{6}</m> of a cup
            </p>
            <p>
              1. How much amount of ingredients is needed to fill the measuring cups of each of the <m>4</m> ingredients.
            </p>
            <p>
              2. Cheruto realizes they accidentally used an additional <m>\frac{1}{6}</m> cup of butter. 
                 How much butter did Cheruto and the chef used in total?
            </p>
            <p>
               3.What is the total amount of ingredients needed for the cake? 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <example>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Oduor a grade <m>8</m> parent wanted to sew a skirt for her daughter.
            She bought <m>2 \frac{2}{3}</m> m of white cloth and <m>2 \frac{1}{4}</m> m of black cloth.
            The tailor used <m>3\frac{1}{3}</m> m of the cloths to make the skirt. Calculate the total length of the cloths that remained.
          </p>  
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                From the above information, lets write an expression.
            </p>
            <p>
             <m>2 \frac{2}{3}</m> m + <m>2 \frac{1}{4}</m> m - <m>3\frac{1}{3}</m> m 
            </p>
            <p>
                Then, convert mixed numbers to improper fractions.
            </p>
            <p>
               <m>\frac{8}{3}</m> m + <m>\frac{9}{4}</m> m - <m> \frac{10}{3}</m> m
            </p>
            <p>
               Applying order of operations, we perform addition:
            </p>
            <p>
               <m>\frac{8}{3}</m> m + <m> \frac{9}{4}</m> m
            </p>
            <p>
                LCM of <m>3</m> and <m>4</m> is <m>12</m> hence
            </p>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow>\frac{8}{3}  \text{m} + \frac{9}{4} \text{m} =\amp \frac{32+27}{12} \text{m} </mrow>
                <mrow> =\amp \frac{59}{12} \text{m}</mrow> 
              </md>
            </p>
            <p>
               Next we rewrite the expression and perform subtraction.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\frac{59}{12}</m> m - <m>\frac{10}{3} </m> m
            </p>
            <p>
               Since the LCM of <m>12</m> and <m>3</m> is <m>12</m> then,
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\frac{59}{12} \text{m} - \frac{10}{3} \text{m}  =\amp  \frac{59-40}{12} \text{m}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{19}{12} \text{m} </mrow>
                </md> 
            </p>
            <p>
                 The fraction <m>\frac{19}{12}</m> m cannot be simplified further therefore we convert the improper fraction to a mixed number.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>= 1\frac{7}{12}</m> m
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Work out the following fraction:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\frac{2}{3} + \frac{2}{7} - \frac{1}{2}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First, find the LCM of the <m>3</m> denominators, that is LCM of <m>3,7</m> and <m>2</m> which is <m>42</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Then using the LCM perform the operations starting from addition followed by subtraction.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                  <mrow> \frac{2}{3} + \frac{2}{7} - \frac{1}{2} =\amp \frac{12+14-21}{42}</mrow>  
                  <mrow> \amp </mrow>
                   <mrow> \frac{12+14-21}{42} =\amp \frac{26-21}{42}</mrow> 
                   <mrow> \amp </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{42} </mrow> 
                </md>   
            </p>
            
        </solution>
    </example>
